<p><strong>What Consumers Are Saying</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>44% say they receive too much spam email and junk mail.</li>
<li>38% say rewards have too many conditions or restrictions.</li>
<li>37% say rewards have little or no value.</li>
<li>35% had a hard time redeeming rewards.</li>
<li>32% felt there was little or no value in becoming a member.</li>
</ul>
<p>Don't miss the carryover here to social media communities. People who Like/Follow brands do so for a number of different reasons; there is no one-size-fits-all approach that works. Don't know what your brand loyalists want? Ask them; they'll be more than happy to tell you.</p>
<p>At the end of the day, remember what matters most both in loyalty programs and in social media is the perceived value by consumers, not the perceived value by brands. Problems arise when there is a disconnect between the two.&nbsp;</p>
<p><span class="full-image-block ssNonEditable"><span><img src="http://wildrumpus.net/storage/post-images/brand-loyalty-infographic-640.jpg?__SQUARESPACE_CACHEVERSION=1316802035901" alt="" /></span></span></p>
<h6>[This post also appears on the <a title="http://bfginteractive.com/blog" href="http://bfginteractive.com/blog" target="_blank">bfg blog</a>.]</h6>]]></description><wfw:commentRss>http://wildrumpus.net/blog/rss-comments-entry-12961612.xml</wfw:commentRss></item><item><title>Facebook Timeline: Exactly What You Never Knew You Always Wanted</title><category>facebook</category><category>privacy</category><category>social media</category><category>timeline</category><dc:creator>Hal Thomas</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 23 Sep 2011 17:26:53 +0000</pubDate><link>http://wildrumpus.net/blog/2011/9/23/facebook-timeline-exactly-what-you-never-knew-you-always-wan.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">492482:5611394:12961131</guid><description><![CDATA[<p><iframe width="640" height="360" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/hzPEPfJHfKU" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>Yesterday, Facebook announced an upcoming feature called Timeline that is meant to make it even easier for people to <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">stalk you online</span> explore the wondrous story that is your life. Call me jaded, but I can't help but wonder if this is really something people want.</p>
<p>We'll have to see how this thing plays out, but it's a clear reminder that what happens on the Internet stays on the Internet&hellip;<em>forever</em>. And now, at least on Facebook, the past is that much easier to uncover.</p>
<p><strong>Remember, people: </strong><a href="http://wildrumpus.net/blog/2011/9/13/oh-no-they-didnt.html">the Internet is a public place</a>.</p>]]></description><wfw:commentRss>http://wildrumpus.net/blog/rss-comments-entry-12961131.xml</wfw:commentRss></item><item><title>Thoughts on Social Media, Publicity, &amp; "Leaked" Information from a Non-Social Media User</title><category>music</category><category>noel gallagher</category><category>oasis</category><category>social media</category><dc:creator>Hal Thomas</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 23 Sep 2011 16:21:27 +0000</pubDate><link>http://wildrumpus.net/blog/2011/9/23/thoughts-on-social-media-publicity-leaked-information-from-a.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">492482:5611394:12960525</guid><description><![CDATA[<p>&nbsp;<object width="576" height="324"><param name="movie" value="http://d.yimg.com/nl/vyc/site/player.swf"></param><param name="flashVars" value="lang=en-US&vid=26677305&"></param><param name="allowfullscreen" value="true"></param><param name="wmode" value="transparent"></param><embed width="576" height="324" allowFullScreen="true" src="http://d.yimg.com/nl/vyc/site/player.swf" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" flashvars="lang=en-US&vid=26677305&"></embed></object></p>
<p>Maybe this is relevant, maybe it isn't. Either way I'm definitely a Noel Gallagher fan. The former principal songwriter for the British rock group Oasis recently sat down for <a title="http://www.nme.com/news/noel-gallagher/59385" href="http://www.nme.com/news/noel-gallagher/59385" target="_blank">an interview with Yahoo! Music</a> to talk about his upcoming release of his first solo album, "Noel Gallagher's High Flying Birds".</p>
<p>At around the 4:30 mark the discussion turns to Twitter, Facebook, and publicity in the Internet age. Gallagher's perspective is, at the very least, entertaining; maybe even a little thought-provoking. Gallagher even reveals that, despite winning an award for maintaining a tour blog during Oasis' last tour, he didn't actually get his first computer until last Christmas.</p>
<p><strong>So what do you think: is the social web contributing to death of magic as Gallagher suggests?</strong></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>A little something for you to mentally chew on this weekend.</p>]]></description><wfw:commentRss>http://wildrumpus.net/blog/rss-comments-entry-12960525.xml</wfw:commentRss></item><item><title>Stat Fest</title><category>Pew Internet</category><category>consumer behavior</category><category>facebook ads</category><category>mobile</category><category>social media</category><category>stats</category><dc:creator>Hal Thomas</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 23 Sep 2011 01:39:00 +0000</pubDate><link>http://wildrumpus.net/blog/2011/9/22/stat-fest.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">492482:5611394:12843098</guid><description><![CDATA[<p>Because you need numbers to back up everything you say these days, here's a quick roundup of statistical and demographic goodness to make your next presentation sound that much smarter.</p>
<ul>
<li>Nielsen released its <a title="http://wearesocial.net/blog/2011/09/nielsen-social-media-report-q3-2011/?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+wearesocial+%28We+Are+Social%29" href="http://wearesocial.net/blog/2011/09/nielsen-social-media-report-q3-2011/?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+wearesocial+%28We+Are+Social%29" target="_blank">Social Media Report</a>.</li>
<li><a title="28% of American adults use mobile and social location-based services" href="28% of American adults use mobile and social location-based services" target="_blank">Pew Internet study</a> says 28% of American adults use mobile and social location-based services. Dirk Singer shares <a title="http://liesdamnedliesstatistics.com/2011/09/14-of-americans-use-location-based-services.html?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+LiesDamnedLiesAndStatistics+%28Lies%2C+damned+lies+and+statistics%29" href="http://liesdamnedliesstatistics.com/2011/09/14-of-americans-use-location-based-services.html?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+LiesDamnedLiesAndStatistics+%28Lies%2C+damned+lies+and+statistics%29" target="_blank">his thoughts</a> on the findings.</li>
<li>A new <a title="http://www.adverveblog.com/2011/09/some-stuff-about-facebook-to-impress-your-boss-with/" href="http://www.adverveblog.com/2011/09/some-stuff-about-facebook-to-impress-your-boss-with/" target="_blank">Facebook research study</a> gives a bunch of stats on Facebook ads that you can use in your next PowerPoint deck.</li>
<li><a title="http://pewinternet.org/Reports/2011/Cell-Phone-Texting-2011.aspx" href="http://pewinternet.org/Reports/2011/Cell-Phone-Texting-2011.aspx" target="_blank">Another Pew Internet study</a> finds that U.S. cell owners between the ages of 18 and 24 exchange an average of 109.5 messages on a normal day. (<em>Do people actually talk face to face these days?)</em></li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;You're welcome.</p>]]></description><wfw:commentRss>http://wildrumpus.net/blog/rss-comments-entry-12843098.xml</wfw:commentRss></item><item><title>Vibram Five Fingers Gets Crowdsourced Video Right</title><category>crowdsourcing</category><category>social media</category><category>strategy</category><category>vff</category><category>vibram five fingers</category><category>video</category><dc:creator>Hal Thomas</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 14 Sep 2011 15:16:44 +0000</pubDate><link>http://wildrumpus.net/blog/2011/9/14/vibram-five-fingers-gets-crowdsourced-video-right.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">492482:5611394:12842795</guid><description><![CDATA[<p><iframe width="640" height="390" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/cYxyo_9DQOg?hd=1" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>One of the mantras of <a href="http://www.vibramfivefingers.com/index.htm">Vibram Five Fingers</a> is this:<strong>&nbsp;Vibram Five Fingers isn't a product, it's a community</strong>. So when Vibram decided to make a video introducing newcomers to its Five Fingers, they proved their mantra wasn't just a cleverly turned phrase of marketing propaganda; they turned to their community of enthusiasts via <a href="http://www.facebook.com/VibramFiveFingers">Facebook</a> and <a href="https://twitter.com/#!/@Vibram5Fingers">Twitter</a>.</p>
<p>The result was over a thousand video submissions from which 100 finalists were chosen. Each finalist received two pairs of "VFF's" (as they are affectionately called by enthusiasts) and one lucky winner was received a VIP Trip to Chamonix to attend the <a href="http://www.ultratrailmb.com/">North Face Ultra-Trail Du Mont-Blanc</a>. More importantly, VFF now has a video introducing newcomers to their product and community with a voice that is as genuine as they come. In fact, you might even say that in this instance, the brand voice is actually the fan voice.</p>
<p>Makes me proud to be <a href="http://instagr.am/p/EPhID/">a member</a> of the VFF community.</p>
<h6>[This post also appears on the <a title="http://bfginteractive.com/blog" href="http://bfginteractive.com/blog" target="_blank">bfg blog</a>.]</h6>]]></description><wfw:commentRss>http://wildrumpus.net/blog/rss-comments-entry-12842795.xml</wfw:commentRss></item><item><title>Oh No They Didn't!</title><category>cover letter</category><category>humor/parody</category><category>stupid tweets</category><dc:creator>Hal Thomas</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 13 Sep 2011 20:30:43 +0000</pubDate><link>http://wildrumpus.net/blog/2011/9/13/oh-no-they-didnt.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">492482:5611394:12833986</guid><description><![CDATA[<p>It's time for another installment of <em>Oh No They Didn't!</em></p>
